# Family Tree SVG Generator — Requirements: In-Laws & Ex-Partners Support

> **Mission:** Extend the existing SVG family tree generator to render in-laws and ex-partners
> as first-class nodes, with distinct visual treatment and relationship edges, without
> disrupting the existing subtree distribution algorithm or the 1:1 aspect ratio constraint.

---

## 1. Background & Constraints

The existing system:
- Generates a hierarchical SVG family tree
- Uses a **subtree distribution algorithm** that splits large trees into smaller subtrees to maintain a **1:1 aspect ratio**
- Nodes are currently assumed to be **blood relatives only**, laid out top-down by generation
- Edges currently represent only **parent → child** relationships

What must not break:
- The subtree distribution logic and its width/height balancing
- The 1:1 aspect ratio enforcement
- Existing node positioning within blood-relative generations
- SVG output format and any existing consumer of it

---

## 2. New Concepts & Definitions

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| **Blood node** | An existing node — a direct biological/adoptive family member |
| **In-law node** | A person who joins the family through marriage/partnership to a blood node |
| **Ex-node** | A former partner (divorced or separated) of a blood node or in-law node |
| **Partner edge** | A horizontal edge connecting two people in a couple (current or former) |
| **Parent edge** | The existing vertical edge from parent(s) to child (unchanged) |
| **Anchor node** | The blood node to whom an in-law or ex-node is attached |

---

## 3. Data Model Changes

### 3.1 Person Node — Add New Fields

Extend the existing person/node object with the following fields:

```json
{
  "id": "string",
  "name": "string",
  "birthYear": "number | null",
  "deathYear": "number | null",

  // --- EXISTING ---
  "parentIds": ["string"],

  // --- NEW ---
  "nodeType": "blood | inlaw | ex",
  "partnerId": "string | null",
  "partnerRelationship": "married | partnered | divorced | separated | widowed",
  "anchorId": "string | null"
}
```

**Field rules:**
- `nodeType` defaults to `"blood"` for all existing nodes — no migration needed
- `anchorId` must be set for every `inlaw` and `ex` node; it points to the blood node they attach to
- `partnerId` is bidirectional — if A's `partnerId` is B, then B's `partnerId` must be A
- An `ex` node may have `parentIds` populated if they are a biological parent of children in the tree
- An `inlaw` node may itself have `nodeType: "inlaw"` children (e.g. in-law's children from a prior relationship) — treat these as `ex` nodes relative to the main tree

### 3.2 Multiple Partners (Remarriage / Serial Relationships)

A blood node may have more than one partner across time. To support this:

```json
{
  "id": "person_A",
  "nodeType": "blood",
  "partners": [
    { "partnerId": "person_B", "partnerRelationship": "divorced", "order": 1 },
    { "partnerId": "person_C", "partnerRelationship": "married",  "order": 2 }
  ]
}
```

- `order` determines left-to-right rendering sequence of partners on the same generation row
- Current/active partner (`married`, `partnered`, `widowed`) renders **closest** to the anchor node
- Ex-partners render **further out** from the anchor node, in reverse chronological order

---

## 4. Layout Algorithm Changes

> **Core principle:** In-law and ex-nodes are **satellites** of their anchor node.
> They must never be treated as independent tree roots or be factored into the
> subtree distribution algorithm as width-generating nodes.

### 4.1 Generation Row Assignment

- In-law and ex-nodes inherit the **same generation row** as their anchor node
- They are placed **horizontally adjacent** to their anchor node on that row
- They do not occupy a slot in the generation's primary node sequence — they are offset laterally

### 4.2 Width Budget Rule

When the subtree distribution algorithm calculates the width of a subtree:

```
subtreeWidth = f(bloodNodes only)
```

In-law and ex-nodes are **excluded from width budget calculations**. After blood node positions are resolved, satellite nodes are placed adjacent to their anchor using a fixed lateral offset:

```
inlawX = anchorNode.x + CARD_WIDTH + PARTNER_GAP
exX    = anchorNode.x - CARD_WIDTH - PARTNER_GAP   // or stacked, see §4.3
```

This means the existing distribution algorithm requires **zero changes to its core logic**.

### 4.3 Multiple Ex-Partners — Stacking Strategy

When a blood node has more than one ex-partner, prevent overlap using one of two strategies. **Choose based on available horizontal space:**

| Strategy | When to use | Layout |
|---|---|---|
| **Horizontal chain** | Fewer than 3 ex-partners | Ex-nodes placed in a horizontal row, each offset by `CARD_WIDTH + PARTNER_GAP` |
| **Staggered offset** | 3 or more ex-partners | Alternate above/below the generation baseline by `±STAGGER_OFFSET` (e.g. ±20px) |

The algorithm must detect overflow (satellite nodes extending beyond the SVG canvas boundary) and fall back to staggered offset automatically.

### 4.4 Children of Divorced/Ex Couples

Children of an ex-couple still appear in the normal child generation row. Their parent edge must fork to connect to **both** parents even if one is an ex-node:

```
child.parentIds = ["blood_node_id", "ex_node_id"]
```

The parent edge renderer must handle the case where one parent is an ex-node and draw the fork accordingly, using the ex-node's resolved position.

