## 8. Acceptance Criteria

The implementation is complete when all of the following pass:

- [ ] An in-law node renders on the same generation row as its anchor, to the right, with a green border and `IN-LAW` badge
- [ ] An ex-node renders on the same generation row as its anchor, with a red dashed partner edge and `EX` badge
- [ ] A divorced partner edge renders as a red dashed line; a married edge renders as a solid grey line
- [ ] Children of a divorced couple connect via a forked parent edge — solid branch to blood parent, dashed branch to ex-parent
- [ ] A node with two ex-partners renders both without overlap (horizontal chain or staggered)
- [ ] The subtree distribution algorithm produces identical output for a tree containing only blood nodes, with or without this feature enabled
- [ ] The 1:1 aspect ratio is maintained for all test cases including trees with in-laws and ex-nodes
- [ ] A legend is present in every SVG output
- [ ] Deceased nodes render in slate regardless of their `nodeType`
- [ ] No satellite node (in-law or ex) extends beyond the SVG canvas boundary

---

## 9. Out of Scope

The following are explicitly **not** required in this change:

- Step-parent / step-sibling relationships (separate ticket)
- Adoption relationships
- Same-generation sibling connectors
- Interactive pan/zoom (SVG is static output)
- Any changes to the subtree split heuristic or aspect ratio algorithm

---

## 10. Suggested Implementation Order

1. Extend the data model and input parser — add `nodeType`, `partners`, `anchorId`
2. Update the node renderer to apply type-based styles and badges
3. Update the edge renderer to handle partner edge types and forked parent edges
4. Add satellite node positioning after blood node layout is resolved
5. Add overflow detection and stagger fallback for multiple ex-partners
6. Add the SVG legend block
7. Run all existing tree test cases to verify no regression
